                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I just read this in a post:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In the most recent PCGamer theres an article showing who controls how much of a share % in the MMO market. 
<br />
FFXI controls some 18%, w/ WoW at about 15%. EQ some 13% and EQ2 at 11%. It included every major mmo short of lineage. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Interesting to see EQ still beats EQ2 in market share.
<br />

<br />
So the question is still as I hoped the other week:  Shouldn't SoE focus on EQ also as a potential product to compete against WoW for the casual players?  I understand SoE has invested a lot of $ into EQ2, and wants to show it off as the future flagship, but it's better to have two MMORPG able to satisfy market trends than one.  Causal player servers can help.
<br />

<br />
Another idea is to implement a mentor program in EQ so the 80% waste land zones of older expansions can be used by more high level people.  It will also help lower level people level up faster.  I was thinking about this mentor thing the other week, but never mentioned it because I thought no one would approve it.
<br />

<br />
Then I saw EQ2's latest announcement that a mentor program will be in place!  So, why not do i t for EQ too.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
