                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Suggestion on a principle in revamping old zones:
<br />

<br />
Another way to merge older player characters with younger player characters is in revamping older zones.  Instead of taking a zone like Paw and making it a fully high level zone, revamp older zones into pockets of high level mobs.  The entry level of Paw may be for level 20s,  Inward deeper might be for level 40.  Behind another door might be level 70 mobs.  The con-system would let players know they should not venture forth when the see gravestone-con mobs.  For another example, in South Karana, insert some non-KOS level 70 aviaks that wander around, or live in a new birdhouse behind the old one.  So while the higher level people run to hunt these pockets, they may pass by the lower level pockets of mobs where lower level characters are hanging out.  Drive-by buffs may be granted this way in a more intimate fashion than in PoK.
<br />

<br />
EQ's tradition was an alignment of zones with exp and loot.  The progression was often from zone to zone.  This divided the player base so that many older zones are vacant.  If each zone has layers of mobs the players can intermingle more.  Of course, currently SoE is counting on $$ from expansions, so this type of revamp is not bringing in money.  But for the long-term health of the game, having layers of mobs in every zone will in the long run prevent wastelands.
<br />

<br />
Suggestion on rare-drop loot for mentors:
<br />

<br />
I know some players love to be mentors.  If a mentor program is instituted, I can already see faces of some people in my mind's eye that will patiently teach newbies every day.  For these kind and patient people, I think it will be nice to have rare-loot drops coded into a mentor program so that a mentor has a small chance for a great loot to appear for him like the rare big wins in the casino system.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
