                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">To get back on topic ....
<br />

<br />
It is clear to EQ2 players that both the EQ1 and EQ2 figures are inflated (to be fair so probably are all the others). In particular there are many EQ2 players, such as myself, that have an EQ1 account and have no intention of playing EQ1 ever again. I have an all access pass for EQ2 reasons and for as long as I do the EQ1 account will be there.
<br />

<br />
The reason the EQ2 figure is inflated is that quite a few people are leaving EQ2, for example when WoW Europe came out many people left, and their accounts are still active.
<br />

<br />
Can WoW players confirm/refute that WoW is losing a steady stream of players too?
<br />

<br />
Please note this is not even a veiled attacked on WoW as it is also clear that WoW is gaining players much faster than it is losing them. Nor is it an attack on EQ2 which equally clearly is gaining some new players.
<br />

<br />
See <a href="http://www.mmogchart.com/" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://www.mmogchart.com/</a> for some interesting charts <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
As a slight diversion do people think the charts show that City of Heroes is dying? and can anyone explain why Runescape has started growing ? It bucks the general trend that games grow fast in the first few months, growth slows down and bumps along, then the games go into a slow decline.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
