                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">But the sum total of EQ1 + EQ2 players is still substantial, even if you estimate that 20% of the players have the SOE All-Pass. The total number of people playing Everquest in one of its forms.
<br />

<br />
As far as "inflated", I don't think there is any real way to determine it since some people come back to a game for short periods of time (ie between school terms), or play other games for a bit and then come back to one, or still intend to play a game sometime in the future. All of the games suffer from that effect.
<br />

<br />
I think the games are really popular based on the "what have you done for us lately?" effect.  Newest game wins for some period of time, simply by virtue of being new and fresh. The real test should only be after the game is at least one year old and two expansions later, so the sustaining power to hold a market would be the test.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
