</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Aithur wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">this is not true for all servers.  I get on and play ever day with almost no problems.  I crashed the other day.. no idea why.  they do have problems but they have been getting better.  of course if you read the forums.. well you will not see that haha.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Same for my server. We are a low population realm and the only lag we experience is when other realms are dropped because of stability issues. The lag has improved, but its far from over. The WoW Official Forums are an example of why I support birthcontrol. If you want information about the game, TheRunes players, FoH Website, and others are where to look. Granted, the WoW Forums at Blizzard do contain a couple meaningful posts occasionally, but their always overshadowed by BNet kiddies. So Aithur is correct, youll never hear the whole story about WoW there.
<br />

<br />
As for people leaving, its a matter of perspective. Mostly the people who raced to the endgame and blew through the content are leaving, many temporarily, until Blizzard implements Battlegrounds and a lot of the nearly completed dungeons like Dire Maul and Caverns of Time. Their waiting for the content patch with as much anticipation as the rest of us, except those of us still playing (like myself) are enjoying the game at an average pace. The hardcore, must get the best of everything players, who didnt stop to smell the roses a bit are the ones leaving permanently and Im glad. This isnt Everquest, and there IS raid content, but Im not concerned with "OMG I MUST BE AT THAT RAID," like I was with EQ, anymore. WoW is a very casual, relaxing game, and I want that trend to continue. So by all means, lets see more powergamers leave, itll help settle stability issues on all the realms as the herd thins out. Youll also notice, that many of the people quitting ARE people not mature enough to play online. The age minimum in WoW is 13, in EQ it was 18; despite seeing grownups act like 13 year olds, people are leaving WoW because Blizzard has a no tolerance policy for morons who hack and cheat. Likewise, their GMs ARE enforcing these policies for all players, unlike EQ who doesnt give a darn. So by all means, headm up and movem out!
<br />

<br />
