<br />

<br />
Very, very true. Im level 54, soon to be 55, and Im not lacking for solo content (much) but I am finding quests starting to become group focused. WoW is definitely more casual, and unlike EQ you CAN pull off events and quests w/o the necessity of a plate tank or pure healer. People raced through to level 60 and complained about lack of content. Well, I realize the leveling pace in WoW is much faster; Im two months (14 days total if you do /played) into my second character (I rerolled new server) and Ive yet to log on and twiddle my thumbs as I did in Everquest as Enchanter. One night I spent 9 hours LFG in PoK, meanwhile in WoW for 9 hours I finished a ton of quests, upgraded several gear slots, made three levels, and felt a sense of accomplishment when I logged. In EQ all I got was my PC crashing when I tried to camp to the server screen. Real rewarding. Do I think theres a lack of content? It depends on what youre interest is. If you want to race to 60, raid 24/7 get the best gear and blow through the game in a matter of days, yea youll be a tad disappointed. But if youre a casual gamer, who logs on a few hours every other day, and is just content with a feeling of accomplishment, youll be quite happy.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Aithur wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">as far as growing numbers for wow.. I think it will grow a little more when they 'officially' let retailers sell them again.  they were pulling games off the selves in some places.  they addeds a bunch of new servers soon after open (I believe they said the used some of their backup servers even)  and just the other day they release 5 new servers.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yep, and while I disagree with opening new servers and not pushing people to play on the low population realms first, the release of so many new realms IS a good sign of WoWs steady growth. Retailers are already restocking shelves, and in my area finding a copy was rare, now there aplenty. In the coming months I can see many more accounts active as Blizzard sorts out stability issues and providing content updates.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Aithur wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">so while undoubtable some are leaving because they are impatient or refused to leave a high population server with problems (and im glad these people left.. I firmly believe in getting rid of the top 10 percent who cause 90 percent of the problems)  there are getting new customers and improving service for the ones they have.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Again, very true. The main attraction to several servers was because of Beta information being leaked, so all the top guilds wanted first dibs on the uber server(s) to fight vs old EQ rivals and the like. Unfortunately, when push came to shove, these people got pissed and left the game because they experienced massive server queues. Its a shame, but the playerbase did this to themselves, it wasnt necessarily all Blizzard. Meanwhile, Blizzard HAS tried to entice people to play elsewhere and created other realms to stave off the growing population, but people need to take advantage of these options voluntarily. Blizzard has suggested character moves being an option, but honestly I dont see them necessary. The leveling curve isnt so bad that you cant be right back where you are within a few weeks (or days as the case may be for some).  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Aithur wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">and unmei, for someone who is tired of hearing people complain about eq.. you sure are hard on wow players.  'its not rocket science..' haha.  well you should know that listening to the bleeding edge content people who burn crap out as fast as possible is never good.  they did the same thing in eq.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />

<br />
There are two types of players in MMORPGs. Players who expect quality, and players who thrive on crumbs. I stopped thriving on crumbs when SoE stopped meeting expectations set forth by the community. You mean they gave us class correspondants? Holy cow SoE is listening now! These are the people who thrive on crumbs. These same people exist in WoW, and they are the fanbois. However, there are those of us who see the true nature of various messages from a company like SoE or Blizzard, and while we enjoy the game, we also realize if they dont start shaping up we WILL quit and move onto something else entirely. The problem is, the crumb thrivers dont want to listen to those of us who say, "dont you think you deserve a lil better?" And thus, arguing ensues. Im not saying people who play EQ suck, but what I am saying is people playing EQ now have a hard time understanding what real communication is and their happy just hearing Brenlo say, "we are listening," and thats not right. By the same token, Blizzard is just as guilty of saying, "we are listening," but you know when their saying it, they mean it, which is why everyone is in such anticipation of this content patch, because its the culmination of four months of community input, developer enhancements, and will ultimately set the tone for what Blizzard (and the playerbase) expect from one another. And if Blizzard fails, miserably, well, youll see me exuding the same comments I do about SoE until its fixed; and if it isnt, well, Ill just move onto something else.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I think wow is going to release in a few more places, but all the big worldwide places may be open now.  did EQII do a worldwide lauch or opening in different parts at different times?  it may pick up even more if so.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
WoW is currently released in Korea, Europe and North America - the big three (theres probably more, I dont know offhand) - and Im not sure if EQ2 did a worldwide release, I think they did.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
